ISX15 SERVICE MANUAL
SECTION 4.2.3 - FUEL SYSTEM SPECIFICATIONS AND DIAGNOSTICS

FUEL PRESSURE SPECIFICATIONS:

Normal Operating Pressure:
- At idle: 25-30 kPa (3.6-4.4 psi)
- Under load: 30-35 kPa (4.4-5.1 psi)
- Minimum acceptable pressure: 20 kPa (2.9 psi)
- Maximum pressure: 40 kPa (5.8 psi)

FUEL SYSTEM COMPONENTS:

Primary Fuel Filter:
- Location: Frame rail, driver side
- Part Number: CUM-FF5485
- Replacement interval: Every 15,000 miles or 1 year
- Micron rating: 10 micron

Secondary Fuel Filter:
- Location: Engine mounted
- Part Number: CUM-FF5633
- Replacement interval: Every 30,000 miles
- Micron rating: 2 micron

Fuel Pump:
- Type: Gear-driven mechanical pump
- Flow rate: 180-220 LPH at idle
- Maximum flow: 250 LPH

LOW FUEL PRESSURE DIAGNOSIS:

If fuel pressure is below 20 kPa, perform the following diagnostic steps:

Step 1: Check Fuel Filter Restriction
- Install fuel pressure gauge at test port
- Start engine and observe pressure
- If pressure is low, check filter restriction
- Replace filter if restriction exceeds 20 kPa

Step 2: Test Fuel Pump Output
- Disconnect fuel return line
- Measure flow rate into container
- Should be minimum 180 LPH at idle
- If below specification, replace fuel pump

Step 3: Inspect Fuel Lines
- Check all fuel lines for:
  * Kinks or restrictions
  * Leaks or cracks
  * Proper routing
- Replace any damaged lines

Step 4: Check Pressure Regulator
- Remove and inspect pressure regulator valve
- Check for:
  * Stuck open condition
  * Debris in valve seat
  * Diaphragm damage
- Clean or replace as needed

COMMON ISSUES AND SOLUTIONS:

Issue: Low fuel pressure with P0171 code
Cause: Typically clogged fuel filter (80% of cases)
Solution: Replace both primary and secondary filters
Time: 45 minutes
Cost: $85 (parts)

Issue: Intermittent fuel pressure drop
Cause: Failing fuel pump (worn gears)
Solution: Replace fuel pump assembly
Time: 3 hours
Cost: $450 (parts + labor)

Issue: High fuel pressure (over 40 kPa)
Cause: Stuck closed pressure regulator
Solution: Replace pressure regulator
Time: 1.5 hours
Cost: $180

SPECIAL TOOLS REQUIRED:

- Fuel pressure test kit (Part# TOOL-FP100)
- Fuel line disconnect tool set (Part# TOOL-FL50)
- Digital multimeter
- Fuel flow meter (optional but recommended)

SAFETY PRECAUTIONS:

1. Allow engine to cool minimum 30 minutes before service
2. Relieve fuel system pressure before disconnecting lines
3. Work in well-ventilated area - fuel vapors are hazardous
4. Have fire extinguisher readily available
5. Disconnect battery negative terminal before starting work
6. Wear safety glasses and fuel-resistant gloves
7. Dispose of old fuel filters according to local regulations

TESTING PROCEDURES:

Fuel Pressure Test:
1. Connect fuel pressure gauge to test port
2. Start engine and allow to reach operating temperature
3. Record pressure at idle
4. Increase RPM to 1500 and record pressure
5. Compare readings to specifications above
6. If pressure is outside range, proceed with diagnosis

Fuel Flow Test:
1. Disconnect return line at tank
2. Route return line into calibrated container
3. Start engine and run for 1 minute
4. Measure fuel volume
5. Should be minimum 3 liters per minute at idle
6. If below spec, pump replacement required

TORQUE SPECIFICATIONS:

- Fuel filter housing bolts: 25 N⋅m (18 lb-ft)
- Fuel pump mounting bolts: 35 N⋅m (26 lb-ft)
- Fuel line fittings: 30 N⋅m (22 lb-ft)
- Pressure regulator bolts: 15 N⋅m (11 lb-ft)